(44, 17, 34, 44, 13, 48, 48, 'believed', 'Connection of Belief and Ordination', 'Both passages emphasize the act of belief among individuals. In Acts 17:34, certain men believed, while Acts 13:48 notes those ordained to eternal life believed.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 34, 23, 55, 10, 11, 'believed', 'The Power of God''s Word', 'This connection highlights the effectiveness of God''s word in bringing forth belief, as seen in Acts where certain men believed. Similarly, Isaiah emphasizes that God''s word will accomplish its purpose, paralleling the transformative impact of the message preached by Paul.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 34, 40, 20, 16, 16, 'believed', 'Belief and Chosen Status', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief leading to being chosen. In Acts 17:34, those who believed, including Dionysius, reflect the idea in Matthew 20:16 that while many are called, few are chosen.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 34, 43, 7, 48, 52, 'believed', 'Belief and Skepticism', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief in Jesus among different groups. In Acts, Dionysius and others believe, while in John, the Pharisees express skepticism about Jesus'' origins.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 34, 43, 19, 38, 42, NULL, 'Discipleship and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of belief and discipleship. In Acts, Dionysius and Damaris represent new believers, while Joseph of Arimathea and Nicodemus are secret disciples of Jesus, highlighting the varied responses to faith.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 1, 46, 1, 2, 2, 'Paul departed from Athens, and came to Corinth', 'Connection Between Paul and Corinth', 'This connection highlights Paul''s journey to Corinth, where he later addresses the church in his letter. Both passages emphasize the significance of Corinth in Paul''s ministry.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 1, 55, 4, 20, 20, 'Corinth', 'Connection Between Corinth References', 'This connection highlights the continuity of Paul''s ministry in Corinth, as both passages mention the location. Acts 18:1 introduces Paul''s arrival in Corinth, while 2 Timothy 4:20 references Erastus, who remained there, indicating ongoing relationships and activities in the same city.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 1, 44, 19, 1, 1, 'Paul departed from Athens, and came to Corinth', 'Paul''s Journey to Ephesus', 'This connection highlights Paul''s movement between cities, first arriving in Corinth and later traveling to Ephesus. Both passages emphasize the continuity of Paul''s missionary work as he moves from one significant location to another.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 1, 47, 1, 1, 1, 'Paul departed from Athens, and came to Corinth', 'Paul''s Mission to Corinth', 'This connection highlights Paul''s journey to Corinth, where he later addresses the church in his letter. Both passages emphasize Paul''s role in establishing and nurturing the Christian community in Corinth.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 1, 44, 17, 15, 15, 'departed from Athens', 'Paul''s Journey to Corinth', 'This connection highlights Paul''s movement from Athens to Corinth. Both passages emphasize the progression of Paul''s missionary journey.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 1, 47, 1, 23, 23, 'came to Corinth', 'Paul''s Journey to Corinth', 'This connection highlights Paul''s movement to Corinth in both passages. Acts 18:1 mentions his arrival in Corinth, while 2 Corinthians 1:23 reflects on his decision regarding visiting Corinth.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 2, 45, 16, 3, 4, NULL, 'Connection of Priscilla and Aquila', 'This connection highlights the relationship between Priscilla and Aquila in both passages. Acts introduces them as companions of Paul, while Romans acknowledges their significant support and sacrifice for him.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 2, 46, 16, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Aquila and Priscilla', 'This connection highlights the presence of Aquila and Priscilla in both passages. They are mentioned in Acts as having come from Rome and later greet the church in 1 Corinthians, indicating their ongoing role in the early Christian community.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 2, 55, 4, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Aquila and Priscilla', 'This connection highlights the continuity of Aquila and Priscilla''s presence in the early church. Both passages emphasize their significance as a couple in the ministry, linking them across different contexts.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 2, 44, 11, 28, 28, 'Claudius had commanded all Jews to depart from Rome', 'Claudius and Jewish Expulsion', 'Both passages emphasize the reign of Claudius, linking his decree affecting Jews in Rome to the prophecy of a famine during his rule. This connection highlights the impact of Claudius''s actions on the early Christian community.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 2, 44, 18, 26, 26, NULL, 'Connection of Aquila and Priscilla', 'This connection highlights the role of Aquila and Priscilla in the early church. Both passages emphasize their involvement in teaching and supporting fellow believers.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 2, 60, 1, 1, 1, 'born in Pontus', 'Connection of Aquila and Pontus', 'This connection highlights the geographical link between Aquila, who was born in Pontus, and the recipients of Peter''s letter, who are also from Pontus. Both passages emphasize the dispersion of Jews and early Christians across regions, indicating a shared cultural and social context.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 3, 46, 4, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Labor and Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of laboring with one''s own hands. Acts 18:3 highlights the occupation of tentmaking, while 1 Corinthians 4:12 speaks of working with our own hands amidst persecution.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 3, 52, 2, 9, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Labor and Preaching', 'This connection highlights the theme of labor in both passages. Acts 18:3 mentions tentmaking as a profession, while 1 Thessalonians 2:9 emphasizes laboring night and day in preaching.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 3, 47, 11, 7, 7, 'for by their occupation they were tentmakers', 'Connection of Labor and Ministry', 'This connection highlights the theme of labor in both passages. In Acts, Paul works as a tentmaker, while in 2 Corinthians, he emphasizes preaching the gospel freely, suggesting a contrast between his physical labor and spiritual service.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 3, 53, 3, 8, 9, 'wrought', 'Work Ethic in Ministry', 'This connection highlights the theme of labor and self-sufficiency in ministry. Both passages emphasize the importance of working diligently, as seen in ''wrought'' and ''labour and travail''.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 3, 47, 12, 13, 13, 'for by their occupation they were tentmakers', 'Connection of Labor and Burden', 'This connection highlights the theme of labor and self-sufficiency. In Acts, Paul works as a tentmaker, while in 2 Corinthians, he emphasizes not being a burden to the church, suggesting a parallel in his approach to ministry and work.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 3, 44, 20, 34, 35, 'wrought: for by their occupation', 'Labor and Generosity Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the value of labor and supporting others. Acts 18:3 mentions tentmaking, while Acts 20:34-35 highlights ministering to needs and the blessing of giving.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 3, 46, 9, 6, 12, 'by their occupation they were tentmakers', 'Work and Spiritual Labor Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of labor in both passages, where Paul discusses the right to receive support for spiritual work in 1 Corinthians, paralleling his own experience as a tentmaker in Acts. Both emphasize the importance of being compensated for one''s labor, whether in physical or spiritual contexts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 4, 47, 5, 11, 11, 'persuaded the Jews and the Greeks', 'Persuasion in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the act of persuading others, whether in the synagogue or in the broader context of faith. This connection highlights the importance of reasoning and convincing others about spiritual truths.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 4, 44, 17, 17, 17, 'reasoned in the synagogue', 'Reasoning in the Synagogue', 'Both passages emphasize the act of reasoning and disputing in the synagogue, highlighting the engagement with Jews and devout persons. This connection illustrates the consistent approach of the speaker in addressing both groups during their ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 4, 44, 28, 23, 23, 'persuaded the Jews and the Greeks', 'Persuasion in the Synagogue', 'Both passages emphasize the act of persuading others about Jesus and the kingdom of God. In Acts 18:4, the focus is on reasoning in the synagogue, while Acts 28:23 highlights expounding from the law and prophets.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 4, 14, 32, 11, 11, 'persuaded the Jews and the Greeks', 'Persuasion in Crisis Contexts', 'This connection highlights the theme of persuasion in both passages. In Acts, Paul persuades Jews and Greeks, while in 2 Chronicles, Hezekiah persuades people regarding their faith in God during a crisis.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 4, 42, 4, 16, 16, 'every sabbath', 'Sabbath Synagogue Practices', 'Both passages emphasize the practice of attending the synagogue on the Sabbath. Acts 18:4 describes reasoning in the synagogue every Sabbath, while Luke 4:16 highlights Jesus'' custom of going into the synagogue on that day.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 4, 42, 16, 31, 31, 'persuaded', 'Persuasion in Faith Contexts', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of persuasion in relation to faith. In Acts, the act of reasoning and persuading is highlighted, while in Luke, the inability to be persuaded despite miraculous signs is noted.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
